The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Friday, February 20, 2004 				 Microsoft signs pact with Orissa
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Bhubaneswar, Feb. 19: The Orissa government today signed a memorandum of understanding with Microsoft to jointly develop and deploy technology solutions for e-governance in the state.																								The MoU, signed for a period of one year, would help the state government outline a blueprint of the IT road map for e-governance.																								As part of the agreement, Microsoft would help in providing IT training to government officials.																								Officials of the IT department said the Orissa Computer Application Centre, a state government undertaking, has been appointed the Strategic Microsoft Technology Partner for the state. It will assist Microsoft in reviewing and deploying the chief ministers information systems, panchayati raj and rural development.																								Asit Kumar Tripathy, the commissioner-cum-secretary in the IT and tourism departments, and Sudev Muthya, director, Enterprise Partner Group, Microsoft Corporation India Pvt. Ltd, signed the MoU, adds PTI.																								Tripathy said the computer centre would develop a core team to work on Microsoft technologies. 																								A centre of excellence would be set up to aid the transfer of Microsoft products and technologies.																								Muthya said todays MoU underlines Microsofts commitment to work with the Orissa government in accelerating the application of its technology in governance and effecting greater transparency and delivery of citizen-centric services.
